[1
Date: Wed, 10 Mar 1999 08:57:55 -0600
From: David A. Watson <dwatson@nsbri.com>

It is interesting to me that, anecdotally at least, what are called
"vaccine failures" may still not be associated with high mortality. Is it
possible that, e.g. the vaccine stimulates the production of antibodies
that do not prevent infection, but which perhaps somehow lessen the
severity the disease? Are there any data that specifically address the
question of mortality rates in the so-called influenza vaccine "failure"
group compared with unvaccinated cohorts?
--
David A. Watson, Ph.D.
Senior Scientist, Information Dynamics
and Associate Professor, University of Texas Medical Branch
