[2
Date: Wed, 10 Mar 1999 07:50:38 -0600
From: Kevin Johnson <kjohnson@hd.co.harris.tx.us>

There are several things that need to be looked at to assess whether or not
a influenza vaccine has failed.
1. Strain of virus causing disease. This can be accomplished with the
cultures that have been obtained.
2. Whether or not the vaccine contained the strain.
The influenza vaccine contains H3N2,H5N1,H1N1,H3N2. If it is a strain
other than these it was not made to protect against it.
It is interesting to me that, anecdotally at least, what are called
"vaccine failures" may still not be associated with high mortality. Is it
possible that, e.g. the vaccine stimulates the production of antibodies
that do not prevent infection, but which perhaps somehow lessen the
severity the disease? Are there any data that specifically address the
question of mortality rates in the so-called influenza vaccine "failure"
group compared with unvaccinated cohorts?
--
Kevin Johnson
Harris County Public Health and Environmental Services
