[3
Date: Wed, 10 Mar 1999 08:42:09 -0600 (CST)
From: David Bergmire-Sweat <David.Bergmire-sweat@tdh.state.tx.us>

The Texas Department of Health has also observed influenza outbreaks in
vaccinated, institutionalized populations this flu season. One outbreak
occurred in a state school population where virtually all of the residents
were vaccinated, and some of the staff. The medical director in that
facility reported that although the ill patients did have clinical and
culture-confirmed influenza A, they were actually tolerating their
illnesses fairly well. It may be that in medically fragile populations the
vaccine will not be completely effective in preventing illnesses, but may
still be important for limiting the severity of disease.
Once again, it is vital to have high vaccination rates among staff as well
as residents in institutional settings, since the literature well documents
that the staff have more contact with the community at large and usually
are responsible for introducing the virus into the institution to begin with.
--
David Bergmire-Sweat, MPH
Staff Epidemiologist
Texas Department of Health
Infectious Disease Epidemiology & Surveillance Division
